                    also <bibl><ptr target="feissel2006"/> <citedRange>914</citedRange></bibl>
                </p>
            </div>
            
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
               
            <ab><lb n="1"/><g ref="symbol.xml#crux"/> <w lemma="ἅγιος">Ἅγιε</w> <persName type="divine" key="paulos"><name  nymRef="Παῦλος">Παῦλε</name></persName> 
                <lb n="2"/><w lemma="καί"><expan><ex>καὶ</ex></expan></w> <persName type="divine" key="germanus"><name nymRef="Γερμανός"><hi rend="ligature">Γε</hi>ρμανέ</name></persName>, <w lemma="σόω">ϲõ
                <lb n="3" break="no"/>ον</w> <orgName ref="#blue"  nymRef="#οἱ Βένετοι"><w lemma="ὁ">τοὺϲ</w> <w lemma="βένετος">Βενέτο
                <lb n="4" break="no"/>υϲ</w></orgName> <w lemma="καί"><expan><ex>καὶ</ex></expan></w> <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="Παπίων">Παπίωνα</name>
                <lb n="5"/> <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="Γεώργιος"><hi rend="ligature">Γε</hi>ωργ̣ίου</name></persName> <w lemma="ἀναγνώστης"><expan><abbr>ἀνα
                <lb n="6" break="no"/>γν</abbr><ex>ώϲτην</ex></expan></w></persName>· <w lemma="ἀμήν">ἀμήν</w></ab>
     </div>
            
            <div type="apparatus"><listApp>
                <app loc="2"><rdg resp="#piccirillo1997">γερμανέ</rdg></app>
                <app loc="5/6"><rdg resp="#piccirillo1997">ἀναγν(ώστου)</rdg></app>
            </listApp></div>
            
            <div type="translation" source="#piccirillo1997" xml:lang="it">
                <p>San Paolo e Germano salva gli Azzurri e Papiona (figlio di) Giorgio il lettore. Amen.</p>
            </div>  
           <div type="translation" resp="#cmr" xml:lang="en">
           <p>Saint Paul and Germanus, save the Blues and Papion, <supplied reason="subaudible">son</supplied> of Georgios, reader. Amen!</p>
                
         </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                
                <p>It is not clear why Saint Paul should be accompanied by a Saint Germanus, and which saint of that name is meant; an alternative, mentioned by Piccirillo, 
                is that this is an epithet, expressing closeness: "Santo e caro Paolo . . . "</p>
            </div>
            
